{
  "text": "Loss of the anti-inflammatory effect of estrogen beginning with menopause is theorized to be responsible for the increasing occurrence of many disorders such as diabetes and its risks [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Some studies have revealed an inflammatory process in the pancreas of patients with type 2 diabetes characterized by the presence of immune cells, cytokines, and β-cell apoptosis [CITATION_4] . Reduction in ovarian function with menopause or surgical procedure has been shown to increase pro-inflammatory cytokines such as IL-1β and TNF-α (3). So, given that both diabetes and ovariectomy can cause inflammation in the pancreas, in this study we investigated the protective effect of genistein on the pancreas of ovariectomized diabetic rat.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "19779962",
    "[CITATION_2]": "24373309",
    "[CITATION_3]": "12782920",
